<hl>
<seg id=1> Shantou New and High Technology Development Zone Attracts Attention of Domestic and Foreign Investors </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News Agency, Shantou, December 20, Telegram.  Due to improvement in the investment environment and good development momentum, the Shantou New and High Technology Development Zone has attracted the attention of domestic and foreign investors.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> A number of scientists originally from Chaozhou who are residing in "Silicon Valley" in the U.S. have indicated their intent to create new and high technology enterprises in the zone.  The CEO of Motorola China and competent personnel at Erricsson Co. have come to the development zone to discuss investment projects.  Taiwanese manufacturers have indicated that they would like to create a technical software development company in the zone. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Currently, a total of 1.8 billion yuan have been invested in the Shantou New and High Technology Development Zone to build 370,000 square meters of plant.  Basic complementary facilities such as water, electricity, communications, and bonded warehouses in the zone have been built and are in use. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Through the beginning of November of this year, a total of 177 projects have come into the zone with a total investment of 6.4 billion yuan.  Of this, foreign capital accounts for about 50 percent.  Among the enterprises that have come into the zone, seven have been recognized as new and high technology enterprises at the national level. </seg>
<seg id=6> This year, the total value of completed industrial production for the entire zone has been 3.7 billion yuan, total income from technical trade has been 4.55 billion yuan, the amount of export trade has been US$127.47 million, and the tax benefit realized has been 360 million yuan. </seg>
<seg id=7> At the same time, the City of Shantou has formulated and implemented more than 10 rules, regulations, and policy measures to encourage the setting up of new and high technology and knowledge-intensive industries. </seg>
</p>
